 animals in relation to ourselves and the polities to which we belong. Setting the saga of human relations with the environment in the broad context of scientific, social, and cultural history, this thought-provoking book demonstrates how profoundly notions of nationality and debates over race and immigration have shaped American understandings of the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aIntroduced organismszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  abiology.  abotany.  aconservation.  aconservationism.  acultural history.  aecological identity.  aenglish sparrow.  aenvironmental conservation protection.  aenvironmental justice.  aenvironmentalism.  aenvironmentalists.  aeucalyptus tree.  ahuman immigration.  ahybridized plants.  ainvading plants.  anative american species.  anatural sciences.  anatural world.  aplant nerds unite.  athought-provoking book.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093325540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933255/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles